></div><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26=
px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Back in April, SpaceX launched the first ever test=
-flight of Starship. The media had a field day back then, as Starship &#822=
0;exploded&#8221; and didn&#8217;t fully accomplish its goals. That&#8217;s=
 partially true &#8212; on test flight one, Starship didn&#8217;t fully sep=
arate into two stages resulting in an explosion. It did, however, launch St=
arship, the tallest and most powerful spacecraft ever flown, and learn a lo=
t in the process. You don&#8217;t get to Mars without blowing up a few mass=
ive rockets, as they say. </p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size=
: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Test flight number two has,=
 basically, the same goals. Launch Starship, separate the two stages, and t=
ake one more small step towards the Artemis Moon Mission. </p><p style=3D"c=
olor: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px=
 0;">When fully operational, Starship will be able to carry up to 100 peopl=
e on long-duration space flights and enable the development of the Moon Bas=
e, send up a shitload of payload cheaply, and ultimately, carry humanity to=
 our second planet. Simply put, in order to get to Mars, we need Starship.<=
/p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; =
margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Also, launching 400 foot rockets into Space is cool.</=
